HyperMorphic Curvature-Activated Representation Locking

A candidate dynamical solution to the quantum measurement problem

Abstract

We formulate quantum measurement as curvature-activated locking of a reversible representation law. The microscopic system, apparatus, environment, and representation register inhabit one Hilbert space. Measurement begins as ordinary unitary entanglement. Nontrivial holonomy among the interaction, amplification, and readout laws then activates a norm-preserving stochastic evolution that selects one pointer branch.

The branch weights are bounded martingales. Consequently, when localization completes, the probability of selecting branch (i) equals its initial Hilbert-space weight:

[
\Pr(i)=\operatorname{Tr}(\rho E_i).
]

Thus the Born rule is obtained dynamically rather than appended as a separate collapse postulate. The ensemble evolution remains a linear completely positive master equation. The model predicts residual, curvature-dependent loss of coherence in otherwise perfectly reversed measurements.

The construction is called HyperMorphic Curvature-Activated Representation Locking, or HCARL.

